Sorry I just captured this.
You don't need to do create a new prop here to handle on success.

You can just simply do onSuccess in the caller
```tsx
mutation.mutate(values, {
  onSuccess: () => {}
});
```
Can we have follow-up PRs to remove this pattern on other deletion hooks?

This is my code:

```
return (
    <>
      <Dropdown menu={{ items: menuItems }} trigger={['click']}>
        <Button type="primary">
          <MoreOutlined />
        </Button>
      </Dropdown>

      {/* Render the EditCatalogModal */}
      {openModal === CreateItemsEnum.Edit && (
        <EditCatalogModal open={true} closeModal={closeModal} />
      )}
    </>
  );
```

You might want to extend this for other usages like `rename`

```suggestion
 enum TableActionsEnum {
    Delete
    Rename
 }
  const [tableAction, setTableAction] = useState<TableActionsEnum | null>(null);
  
  // usage 
  setTableAction(TableActionsEnum.Delete)
  <Modal open={tableAction === TableActionsEnum.Delete} closeModal={() => setTableAction(null) />
```
